      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "da1468fa3b7cc5b9e1f2c1330de8f2421f781e60",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-18 22:50:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nActually I already remove these lmv_object in my DNE branch. Just use lmv_stripe information in lmv layer, which should be land to 2.2.\n\nThe patch itself looks good to me. But I probably prefer to not touch these lmv code, otherwise I might need take extra efforts to sync my branch? Sorry about this. \n\nBut if you see a big performance improvement from this patch, I do not mind you land it. Thanks.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "4ee0b2193c31f757a827e70c28c960ed938c7bf4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-25 14:27:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nThe unnecessary CMD lock process is on critical paths for almost all the client-side VFS operations. That is good if you have removed those locks in your patch. Can you split related patch from your DNE branch and land it firstly? I will land my patches to lustre-2.2 as schedule, and not depend on other project(s). Anyway I will have to fix other LMV code (in other patches) for non-lock purposes. I am not sure whether it will affect your work.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "cc0bda302d87a2f4585d14a7fbd89b88ebee9b04",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-25 14:52:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nOn the other hand, the main change in the patch is the bypass processing inside \"lmv_object_find()\" and \"lmv_find_target()\", which are common interfaces for others. The caller need to change nothing for that. So even if there is merge conflict with your patch, the conflit will be less that 10 lines in one hunk.\n\nAnyway LMV is the only way for traversing directory process. So I have no change/add something in LMV.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "fbf3a2cf3205516479daa39cdd4102a5dc4acb45",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-08-25 15:02:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> Anyway LMV is the only way for traversing directory process. So I have no change/add something in LMV.\n\nSorry, typo. I have to add/del/modify something in LMV layer.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
